725481f-c.title: Queens: 57th Avenue - 58th Street
725481f-c.text:
Fifty-seventh Ave. (foreground), just east of 58th Street
(right), showing in a set of four views the former summer home of
Gov. De Witt Clinton.
1922.
Views 1 and 2.
View 3: March 1925.
View 4: September 1929.

725491f-d.title: Queens: 58th Street - 57th Road
725491f-d.text:
58th Street, east side, between 57th Road and 57th Drive,
showing in a set of four views the Episcopal Church of St.
Saviours. This church was erected on land donated by James
Maurice in 1840. lIts cornerstone was laid by Bishop Potter on
November 1, 1847 and the edifice concentrated on January 28, 1848.
Views 3 and 4 look northward from 57th Drive.
1922.
Views 2 \& 4: March 1925.
View 3: January 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.

725480f-a.title: Queens: 57th Avenue - 58th Street
725480f-a.text:
57th Avenue, just east of 58th -treet, showing the Sackett
homesteac, built about 1700 by 'oseph Sacket. It is best
known as the country home of Governor DeWitt Clinton. It
was s1so the home of Walter Franklin, a prominent New York
merchant.

725482f-b.text:
